      <h2>Origins in Europe</h2>
      <p>The harmonium was invented in Paris in the early 19th century, with Alexandre Debain receiving the first patent in 1842. The instrument used free reeds — thin metal tongues that vibrated in passing air — producing a rich sustained tone unlike any existing keyboard instrument. It quickly spread across Europe as an affordable alternative to pipe organs in homes and small churches.</p>

      <h2>Arrival in India</h2>
      <p>The harmonium arrived in India during British colonial rule primarily through Christian missionaries who used it in church services and mission schools. Initially it was associated exclusively with Western Christian music. But Indian musicians quickly recognized its potential — particularly its ability to sustain a drone note indefinitely while the right hand played melody.</p>

      <h2>The AIR Ban and Its Consequences</h2>
      <p>In 1940 All India Radio (AIR) banned the harmonium from its broadcasts arguing the instrument could not produce the subtle microtonal inflections (gamak, meend) essential to Indian classical music and that its fixed pitch tuning distorted the natural pitch variations of the human voice. The ban lasted until 1971 during which time harmonium continued to flourish in live performance even while excluded from radio.</p>

      <h2>Integration into Indian Music</h2>
      <p>Despite controversies the harmonium became inseparable from Indian music across virtually all genres. In Hindustani classical it accompanies vocalists in the Kirana and Jaipur gharanas. In devotional music it leads bhajans kirtan and qawwali. In Bollywood it has been used in studio recordings since the 1930s. In folk music it provides melody across Punjab Rajasthan and Bengal.</p>

      <h2>Modern Legacy</h2>
      <p>Today the harmonium is played by millions of Indians making it perhaps the most widely used melodic instrument in the country. From Ustad Bade Ghulam Ali Khan being accompanied on harmonium in classical concerts to Pandit Bhimsen Joshi's legendary harmonium accompanists to kirtan leaders in temples across India the instrument has become as distinctly Indian as any indigenous instrument.</p>

